article.headline: Duke wins 38th straight conference game in rout
article.linkText: Duke clinches third ACC regular-season title
article.story:
COLLEGE PARK, Md. (AP) -- Despite clinching the ACC regular-season title, Duke coach Gail Goestenkors was extremely dissatisfied.

	   "I'm very disappointed in our overall effort, extremely
disappointed,'' Goestenkors said. "We got outhustled. They took
some balls out of our hands. We put them on the free throw line in
the second half, allowed them to penetrate, didn't do a good job
getting offensive rebounds. It was unacceptable.''

	   Yet it was way more than enough for the Blue Devils.

	   Lindsey Harding scored a career-high 19 points and Alana Beard
scored 18 as No. 2 Duke beat Maryland 97-55 Monday night, clinching
their third consecutive conference title.

	   Duke (26-1, 14-0 ACC) won all 16 of its conference games last
season.

	   The Blue Devils controlled play from the opening tip, extending
their ACC winning streak to 38 games. They routed Maryland (10-16,
4-11) 101-52 on Jan. 23 and the Terrapins have lost six straight to
Duke.

	   Senior Renneika Razor missed her last home game as a Terrapin
because of a concussion suffered during Maryland's loss to Virginia
on Thursday. Razor is the team's leading scorer and the ACC steals
leader.

	   "In spite of adversity, we should be proud of how we battled,''
Maryland coach Brenda Frese said. "We were without our leading
player and with the players we had out there, I thought they
battled.''

	   Duke won it with a dominant first half, leading 41-14 at the
break. The Blue Devils opened with a 19-1 run, holding Maryland to
0-for-16 from the field.

	   Maryland also succumbed to Duke's strong full-court press,
turning the ball over 24 times, including 14 in the first half.

	   Beard, a Naismith Award and Wade Trophy finalist, was limited to
10 minutes in the first half because of two early fouls. Despite
her foul trouble, Beard became the third player in ACC history to
amass 300 steals, 500 rebounds, and 350 assists, while moving into
21st place on the ACC's career scoring list.

	   Beard felt Harding was the deciding factor for the Blue Devils.

	   "Lindsey comes out and gives the other point guard a lot of
trouble,'' Beard said. "She knows the game really well for a point
guard. She can take the outside shot, take it inside, she can do it
all. That's what we need, to add another dimension to our starting
lineup.''

	   In Razor's absence, freshman Chrissy Fisher led the Terrapins
with 15 points and six rebounds.

	   Despite outrebounding the Blue Devils 42-37, the other Terrapins
could not produce any offense. Duke's tight defense allowed
Maryland few inside shots.
